00:03:22.040 --> 00:03:24.080
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS HOLBROOK:
Thank you very much.

00:03:24.080 --> 00:03:27.430
Raise your hand if
you can't hear me.

00:03:27.430 --> 00:03:31.630
Am I all right with you?

00:03:31.630 --> 00:03:34.790
Tomorrow, I'm talking mostly

00:03:34.790 --> 00:03:38.340
about printing types although a
few other things will work their

00:03:38.340 --> 00:03:43.040
way in and today I'm talking
not so much about victor's work

00:03:43.040 --> 00:03:47.690
as a typographer and printer,
but will be happy to do

00:03:47.690 --> 00:03:52.870
so in discussion with you
after my presentation.

00:03:52.870 --> 00:03:56.010
Today my hope is to introduce
you to victor [inaudible]

00:03:56.010 --> 00:04:00.430
and his work and then when I
have done so, you will feel

00:04:00.430 --> 00:04:03.960
as if you have met him.

00:04:05.100 --> 00:04:09.850
In a letter of May, the 25st,
1951, the poet Wallace Stevens

00:04:09.850 --> 00:04:13.140
with whom [inaudible] had
an extensive correspondence

00:04:13.140 --> 00:04:17.230
and for whom victor
created an [inaudible],

00:04:17.230 --> 00:04:21.930
humorously suggested the life
and times of a contrary man

00:04:21.930 --> 00:04:26.090
as a suitable title
for [inaudible] book

00:04:26.090 --> 00:04:30.730
which was badly entitled as
Memory and her nine daughters,

00:04:30.730 --> 00:04:34.320
the muses, a pretext for
printing cast into the mold

00:04:34.320 --> 00:04:36.490
of a dialogue in 4 chapters.

00:04:36.490 --> 00:04:38.900
It was badly entitled because I

00:04:38.900 --> 00:04:43.220
as a sometime bibliographer have
had to write the entire title

00:04:43.220 --> 00:04:47.970
or type it numerous
times, too long.

00:04:47.970 --> 00:04:50.370
I, being in the process
of writing a biography

00:04:50.370 --> 00:04:53.140
of [inaudible] at the request
of his late wife Caroline,

00:04:53.140 --> 00:04:55.690
with whom I worked for 30 years,

00:04:55.690 --> 00:05:01.230
and considering using this title
humorously suggested by Stevens

00:05:01.230 --> 00:05:06.100
as the subtitle of my
biography of [inaudible].

00:05:06.100 --> 00:05:11.260
[inaudible] himself says in
the dialogue lengthily titled,

00:05:11.260 --> 00:05:14.260
truly I'm, you labeled
me the contrary man,

00:05:14.260 --> 00:05:17.920
but you did not say
contrary to what.

00:05:17.920 --> 00:05:21.410
Truly I'm contrary to mediocrity
though I know we could not live

00:05:21.410 --> 00:05:23.180
on the planet without it.

00:05:23.180 --> 00:05:27.370
I'm contrary to sloth and
contrary to waste which will go

00:05:27.370 --> 00:05:29.720
on in spite of me
and I'm contrary

00:05:29.720 --> 00:05:32.430
to blasphemy against the spirit.

00:05:32.430 --> 00:05:35.480
I have proved to myself
that I can change the world,

00:05:35.480 --> 00:05:38.320
that only within the
reach of my hands.

00:05:38.320 --> 00:05:41.950
The work I leave behind will
not be great yet it will prove

00:05:41.950 --> 00:05:47.880
to be genuine, genuine
though not progressive.

00:05:47.880 --> 00:05:51.680
[inaudible] poets in ancient
India saw that all elements

00:05:51.680 --> 00:05:55.880
of the divine, human and natural
world fit together perfectly

00:05:55.880 --> 00:05:59.290
in an eternal and smoothly
flowing symbolism known

00:05:59.290 --> 00:06:01.670
as [inaudible].

00:06:01.670 --> 00:06:04.210
Despite their powerful
and diverse personalities,

00:06:04.210 --> 00:06:06.890
even the gods and goddesses
lived within the structure

00:06:06.890 --> 00:06:10.580
of this cosmic law
of universal harmony.

00:06:10.580 --> 00:06:13.460
With intuitive flash of
imagination, the poet

00:06:13.460 --> 00:06:17.370
or artist was able to see
the unified harmonious nature

00:06:17.370 --> 00:06:21.870
of reality and to be afforded
access to the creative powers

00:06:21.870 --> 00:06:24.480
that imagined the real.

00:06:24.480 --> 00:06:27.780
The sand script word
[inaudible] suggests the smooth

00:06:27.780 --> 00:06:31.230
and rhythmic turning of the
wheel of being and is derived

00:06:31.230 --> 00:06:35.000
from the proto-Indo-European
root, ar,

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:39.810
meaning fit together
properly, suitably united.

00:06:39.810 --> 00:06:43.280
This serves as the basis
for the Greek word harmous,

00:06:43.280 --> 00:06:47.390
the root of harmony and also
the basis for the Latin ar's,

00:06:47.390 --> 00:06:49.890
root of art and artist.

00:06:49.890 --> 00:06:52.940
The [inaudible] sages who
saw [inaudible] within

00:06:52.940 --> 00:06:57.790
and behind all forms of being
saw the art of existence itself

00:06:57.790 --> 00:06:59.770
and allowed their
artistry and craft

00:06:59.770 --> 00:07:03.760
to focus the creative power
and thereby to present

00:07:03.760 --> 00:07:06.510
that order fixed
for contemplation.

00:07:06.510 --> 00:07:09.040
[ Background noise ]

00:07:09.040 --> 00:07:10.340
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS HOLBROOK:
Victor [inaudible] life

00:07:10.340 --> 00:07:13.300
as an artist and craftsman is
a testament to that vision.

00:07:13.300 --> 00:07:16.700
It is an understanding that
very early became a part

00:07:16.700 --> 00:07:19.740
of [inaudible] tacit awareness.

00:07:19.740 --> 00:07:24.710
As he writes in his last book,
I was born into the 18th century

00:07:24.710 --> 00:07:26.490
yet I was not consciously aware

00:07:26.490 --> 00:07:29.230
of this fact for
a very long time.

00:07:29.230 --> 00:07:32.990
I first opened my eyes in and
onto one of the oldest parts

00:07:32.990 --> 00:07:37.140
of Vienna, the Vienna
of Maria Teresa.

00:07:37.140 --> 00:07:39.810
My father and mother had chosen
to live in this old sector

00:07:39.810 --> 00:07:42.490
of time not because
it was beautiful,

00:07:42.490 --> 00:07:45.680
but because the rents
were low for not one

00:07:45.680 --> 00:07:50.360
of the houses had more than the
simplest conveniences to offer.

00:07:50.360 --> 00:07:54.430
I was born in [inaudible],
but my earliest recollections,

00:07:54.430 --> 00:07:56.330
all of them visual, hinge

00:07:56.330 --> 00:08:00.890
on the place we occupied
in the [inaudible].

00:08:00.890 --> 00:08:04.050
These first few years of my
childhood in the last quarter

00:08:04.050 --> 00:08:07.030
of the 19th century have
formed by view of the world

00:08:07.030 --> 00:08:10.520
as an artist and have modeled
it in the character of the art

00:08:10.520 --> 00:08:14.000
of the late 17th and
early 18th centuries.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:18.320
I had no chance, nor had I
being then a little oy not

00:08:18.320 --> 00:08:22.190
yet in school, the capacity
for realizing that all things

00:08:22.190 --> 00:08:27.080
that surrounded me were
already over 200 years old.

00:08:27.080 --> 00:08:29.860
This world into which I was
born and in which I began

00:08:29.860 --> 00:08:32.880
to live was a world
contemporary with me.

00:08:32.880 --> 00:08:34.810
I saw no other.

00:08:34.810 --> 00:08:37.310
It was a world built of
the demand of the people

00:08:37.310 --> 00:08:40.870
who lived more than 2 centuries
before me, a world shaped

00:08:40.870 --> 00:08:43.760
and raised by their
builders and artists,

00:08:43.760 --> 00:08:47.040
a world of artistic achievements
was the only world of which I,

00:08:47.040 --> 00:08:49.770
at this early age, was aware.

00:08:49.770 --> 00:08:53.380
It was self-evident and
beyond all question.

00:08:53.380 --> 00:08:55.550
I had never heard of art,

00:08:55.550 --> 00:08:58.820
would not have understood the
word nor could I have conceived

00:08:58.820 --> 00:09:02.900
of quality and achievement, but
I looked upon the altar pieces

00:09:02.900 --> 00:09:06.150
in the Jesuit's church,
it's ceiling with a fresco

00:09:06.150 --> 00:09:11.060
by Padre Patso and
[inaudible] of the university.

00:09:11.060 --> 00:09:14.260
I absorbed and accepted,
unknowingly.

00:09:14.260 --> 00:09:17.440
I am a genuine anachronism.

00:09:17.440 --> 00:09:20.300
The rear of the Jesuit's
church, it's apse,

00:09:20.300 --> 00:09:24.760
gave on the [inaudible], the
front gave on the [inaudible].

00:09:24.760 --> 00:09:29.020
The house in which we lived
was separated from the church

00:09:29.020 --> 00:09:33.410
by a narrow passageway
only allowed to pedestrians

00:09:33.410 --> 00:09:36.010
as it opened through
no more than a doorway

00:09:36.010 --> 00:09:39.880
into the [inaudible]
where the church stood.

00:09:39.880 --> 00:09:43.750
I liked to play or just
to be in this place.

00:09:43.750 --> 00:09:46.600
Every time I stepped through
the small doorway into this roof

00:09:46.600 --> 00:09:49.910
without a ceiling through
4 well-ordered walls,

00:09:49.910 --> 00:09:53.410
the site of it cleared my
breath, made me feel free.

00:09:53.410 --> 00:09:56.730
Even the memory of it
has the same affect.

00:09:57.790 --> 00:10:01.180
This well-ordered space was
the womb which nurtured the art

00:10:01.180 --> 00:10:04.190
of victor [inaudible] in his
youth and set the trajectory

00:10:04.190 --> 00:10:08.530
that allowed his vision to
develop throughout his lifetime.

00:10:08.530 --> 00:10:11.560
[inaudible] attended 4 years of
the Jesuit's elementary school,

00:10:11.560 --> 00:10:13.930
already showing a vivid
interest in drawing,

00:10:13.930 --> 00:10:16.080
painting and the crafts.

00:10:16.080 --> 00:10:18.780
Because of his artistic
bent as he grew older,

00:10:18.780 --> 00:10:21.770
his father became
concerned about his future,

00:10:21.770 --> 00:10:23.860
fearing that life as an
artist could not be a

00:10:23.860 --> 00:10:26.110
serious profession.

00:10:26.110 --> 00:10:28.800
At 14, after 4 years
of secondary school

00:10:28.800 --> 00:10:32.440
with increases competence as
a draftsman, several drawings

00:10:32.440 --> 00:10:35.410
of his family including a
portrait of his grandfather

00:10:35.410 --> 00:10:38.370
which had recently
gained familial favor,

00:10:38.370 --> 00:10:40.550
finally convinced his father

00:10:40.550 --> 00:10:43.800
that his artistic
ambitions were serious.

00:10:43.800 --> 00:10:46.510
No longer opposing
victor's future plans,

00:10:46.510 --> 00:10:50.140
Carl [inaudible] arranged for
his apprenticeship in the studio

00:10:50.140 --> 00:10:52.360
of the well-known
architect, art historian

00:10:52.360 --> 00:10:57.650
and urban planner,
[inaudible] in 1897.

00:10:57.650 --> 00:11:01.040
After a year of realizing
victor's potential, he suggested

00:11:01.040 --> 00:11:03.900
that he should apply to
the academy of fine arts.

00:11:03.900 --> 00:11:05.890
He was accepted and
studied painting

00:11:05.890 --> 00:11:07.190
with professor [inaudible].

00:11:07.190 --> 00:11:11.700
Later he switched to sculpture
classes with professors Helmer,

00:11:11.700 --> 00:11:13.000
[inaudible] and [inaudible].

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:14.300
[ Background noise ]

00:11:14.300 --> 00:11:15.600
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS HOLBROOK:
He was very much attracted

00:11:15.600 --> 00:11:16.900
to sculpture but soon realize

00:11:16.900 --> 00:11:19.860
that his true métier
was to be painting.

00:11:19.860 --> 00:11:22.660
As he said, I could not
afford to be a sculptor

00:11:22.660 --> 00:11:25.640
and I knew I could make
my way as a painter.

00:11:25.640 --> 00:11:29.630
Though when I looked at a
finished work, I am always aware

00:11:29.630 --> 00:11:32.340
that I painted with
a sculptor's eye.

00:11:32.340 --> 00:11:34.730
My painted figures
looked to be carved.

00:11:34.730 --> 00:11:40.590
He left the academy after 7
semesters saying professor

00:11:40.590 --> 00:11:43.600
[inaudible] was glad to be
rid of me as glad as he was

00:11:43.600 --> 00:11:46.990
to have rid himself
of [inaudible].

00:11:46.990 --> 00:11:50.520
He worked alone for a year
when professor [inaudible] work

00:11:50.520 --> 00:11:54.650
and took him into his classes
where he remained for 4 years.

00:11:54.650 --> 00:11:56.810
While there, he participated
for the first time

00:11:56.810 --> 00:12:00.120
in a public exhibition
with the [inaudible],

00:12:00.120 --> 00:12:03.520
an artist organization, in 1907.

00:12:03.520 --> 00:12:06.110
His portrait of a woman
was received positively

00:12:06.110 --> 00:12:08.300
by the press and critics.

00:12:08.300 --> 00:12:10.550
His next success came in 1908

00:12:10.550 --> 00:12:13.880
when he was awarded the
[inaudible] for a portrait

00:12:13.880 --> 00:12:18.030
of Rosa [inaudible], his future
wife, which allowed him to marry

00:12:18.030 --> 00:12:22.330
and to travel to Paris, Munich,
and for the first time to Italy.

00:12:22.330 --> 00:12:25.680
He also won the [inaudible],
permitting further traveling.

00:12:25.680 --> 00:12:29.000
They spent the winter
of 1909 and 10 in Munich

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:30.650
and became acquainted
with the circle

00:12:30.650 --> 00:12:34.470
around Adolf von [inaudible], a
friend of the artist [inaudible]

00:12:34.470 --> 00:12:36.090
and the art theorist
Conrad [inaudible].

00:12:36.090 --> 00:12:41.070
[inaudible] writes in 1910
or 11, I had an interview

00:12:41.070 --> 00:12:43.080
with Adolf von [inaudible].

00:12:43.080 --> 00:12:46.470
His book, the problem of
form, had fascinated me,

00:12:46.470 --> 00:12:49.220
but I felt I did not
understand it and hoped

00:12:49.220 --> 00:12:52.300
that he would explain
part of it to me.

00:12:52.300 --> 00:12:54.430
He tried, but after quite
a long talk together,

00:12:54.430 --> 00:12:56.950
I was still groping
for my answers.

00:12:56.950 --> 00:13:00.190
Finally, I asked a question
which I thought was pertinent,

00:13:00.190 --> 00:13:02.540
after all, is not the
most important part

00:13:02.540 --> 00:13:05.430
of the portrait painter's
task the representation

00:13:05.430 --> 00:13:08.270
of the psyche of the sitter.

00:13:08.270 --> 00:13:11.080
With a flash in his
eyes, he hurled a reply,

00:13:11.080 --> 00:13:13.520
how can you say such a thing.

00:13:13.520 --> 00:13:18.070
I was shocked and crushed,
but my eyes had been opened.

00:13:18.070 --> 00:13:20.990
In time, I understood.

00:13:20.990 --> 00:13:24.280
Because of his contact with
[inaudible], he said of his stay

00:13:24.280 --> 00:13:26.590
in Munich, this experience
brought by a deep

00:13:26.590 --> 00:13:29.830
and lasting spiritual
stimulation.

00:13:29.830 --> 00:13:32.820
From [inaudible], he began to
understand the problem of form

00:13:32.820 --> 00:13:36.020
in a clearer light with
form as the primary concern

00:13:36.020 --> 00:13:38.530
of the artist, but it
would be several years

00:13:38.530 --> 00:13:42.600
until his understanding became
visible in his paintings.

00:13:42.600 --> 00:13:47.190
[inaudible] had been painting
of rather large canvases

00:13:47.190 --> 00:13:48.940
and a colleague suggested
smaller,

00:13:48.940 --> 00:13:51.750
more intimate portraits
more likely to be bought

00:13:51.750 --> 00:13:55.860
and fitting more easily
in domestic settings.

00:13:55.860 --> 00:13:57.990
Indeed, [inaudible]
received more

00:13:57.990 --> 00:14:00.220
and more private commissions.

00:14:00.220 --> 00:14:04.400
The [inaudible] ought a portrait
[inaudible] in an easy chair

00:14:04.400 --> 00:14:07.470
at which time he also took
up book binding in order

00:14:07.470 --> 00:14:09.900
to supplement his
income as an artist.

00:14:09.900 --> 00:14:12.420
This is a portrait
of [inaudible],

00:14:12.420 --> 00:14:15.230
done in almost art nuevo style.

00:14:15.230 --> 00:14:19.710
She was a dancer, I mean,
well dancer and singer

00:14:19.710 --> 00:14:23.770
in the Viennese Operetta.

00:14:23.770 --> 00:14:28.840
In 1912, he exhibited a
collection in the succession.

00:14:28.840 --> 00:14:31.510
It was an important success
critically and financially

00:14:31.510 --> 00:14:34.080
and he was elected a
member of the succession

00:14:34.080 --> 00:14:37.570
and joined regular
commissions thereafter.

