From 1907 until world war 1, he
exhibited regularly at galleries

00:14:41.730 --> 00:14:44.000
in Vienna, in Berlin at
the gallery [inaudible]

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:46.240
and in Munich at the
gallery [inaudible].

00:14:46.240 --> 00:14:49.230
He was mentioned positively,

00:14:49.230 --> 00:14:51.670
almost unanimously,
in publications.

00:14:51.670 --> 00:14:54.840
Only once was he
criticized for his quote,

00:14:54.840 --> 00:14:57.020
sharp and rigidly
drawn portraits

00:14:57.020 --> 00:14:59.760
which lacked liveliness.

00:14:59.760 --> 00:15:04.050
[inaudible] resigned from the
Viennese succession in 1913,

00:15:04.050 --> 00:15:06.180
realizing he had
really nothing in common

00:15:06.180 --> 00:15:09.990
with the other secessionist even
though they were his classmates

00:15:09.990 --> 00:15:13.540
at the academy.

00:15:13.540 --> 00:15:16.200
Indeed, [inaudible],
who recently had a show

00:15:16.200 --> 00:15:20.550
at the Neue Gallery in New
York, had been his studio mate

00:15:20.550 --> 00:15:24.230
at the time of [inaudible]
tragic suicide following his

00:15:24.230 --> 00:15:27.560
affair with Matilda [inaudible].

00:15:29.030 --> 00:15:33.320
This is a [inaudible]
self-portrait with clarinet

00:15:33.320 --> 00:15:40.450
in oil showing still bound to
the Viennese style of 1900.

00:15:40.450 --> 00:15:45.060
In his studies, victor had
copied portraits of [inaudible]

00:15:45.060 --> 00:15:47.380
and the Italian masters
as well as [inaudible]

00:15:47.380 --> 00:15:51.780
of the Austrian Biedermeier,
whom he admired very much.

00:15:51.780 --> 00:15:54.610
In all the early portraits,
[inaudible] technique differed

00:15:54.610 --> 00:15:56.610
from that of his
later paintings.

00:15:56.610 --> 00:16:00.480
He painted in oil instead of
egg tempera and in a much freer

00:16:00.480 --> 00:16:06.080
and quicker way, finishing
after only a few sittings.

00:16:06.080 --> 00:16:10.260
[inaudible] completed 2
early portraits of his friend

00:16:10.260 --> 00:16:14.500
and patron, [inaudible]
as well as a couple

00:16:14.500 --> 00:16:19.600
of self-portraits all in
oil, this being one of them.

00:16:19.600 --> 00:16:22.020
[inaudible] had been a road
scholar at Oxford together

00:16:22.020 --> 00:16:24.510
with Alexander [inaudible].

00:16:24.510 --> 00:16:30.040
[ Background noise ]

00:16:30.040 --> 00:16:31.340
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS
HOLBROOK: By 1914,

00:16:31.340 --> 00:16:38.330
there was movement toward the
later style with the portraits

00:16:38.330 --> 00:16:45.160
of Helen [inaudible]
and his great friend

00:16:45.160 --> 00:16:46.660
and patron, Conrad [inaudible].

00:16:46.660 --> 00:16:50.450
This is the portrait
of [inaudible].

00:16:50.450 --> 00:16:51.890
She is dressed in green.

00:16:51.890 --> 00:16:58.340
Unfortunately, we don't
seem to have a color copy.

00:16:58.340 --> 00:17:00.680
Both portraits display
his meticulous treatment

00:17:00.680 --> 00:17:04.310
of every detail, a facet
of all future work,

00:17:04.310 --> 00:17:08.340
but he says I can only give my
sitter's head the best place

00:17:08.340 --> 00:17:10.250
on the panel.

00:17:10.250 --> 00:17:13.300
The portraits of Conrad and Ana
[inaudible] each display letter

00:17:13.300 --> 00:17:17.030
forms, announcing the subject's
name and date of completion.

00:17:17.030 --> 00:17:20.260
[inaudible] often continues
this painting of letter forms

00:17:20.260 --> 00:17:21.700
in his work in the medieval

00:17:21.700 --> 00:17:26.030
and early renaissance
style in various portraits.

00:17:26.030 --> 00:17:30.650
[inaudible] writes in May
of 1914, I was invited

00:17:30.650 --> 00:17:32.240
by [inaudible] to
come to Florence

00:17:32.240 --> 00:17:34.590
and paint a portrait
of his wife.

00:17:34.590 --> 00:17:37.090
I worked very hard on this
portrait in the few weeks

00:17:37.090 --> 00:17:39.720
at their Villa in
[inaudible] near Florence,

00:17:39.720 --> 00:17:43.200
was a very lovely
time in my life.

00:17:43.200 --> 00:17:45.690
I was able to take a trip
by car through Umbria

00:17:45.690 --> 00:17:49.560
and the total experience
filled me with pure happiness.

00:17:49.560 --> 00:17:51.670
Faith had apparently
given me this peaceful

00:17:51.670 --> 00:17:54.270
and happy interlude
out of charity

00:17:54.270 --> 00:17:59.350
for before I could start my new
work, the world war broke out.

00:17:59.350 --> 00:18:02.730
I reported for duty in
[inaudible], Poland,

00:18:02.730 --> 00:18:05.530
on the [inaudible]
river as an infantryman.

00:18:05.530 --> 00:18:07.370
He spent 4 months in combat

00:18:07.370 --> 00:18:10.570
with the 4th Austrian
infantry regiment.

00:18:10.570 --> 00:18:13.650
In October, he would be sent
to guard duty behind the lines

00:18:13.650 --> 00:18:17.470
and then to headquarters as a
staff artist in the [inaudible].

00:18:17.470 --> 00:18:19.960
After the war, [inaudible] was
sent to [inaudible] and then

00:18:19.960 --> 00:18:23.360
to Constantinople before
returning to Vienna.

00:18:23.360 --> 00:18:26.560
He writes, the first work I
did after this army life was

00:18:26.560 --> 00:18:30.130
as though my artistic
ability was paralyzed.

00:18:30.130 --> 00:18:33.670
In the first year at the
academy, my work was better.

00:18:33.670 --> 00:18:41.020
In 1918, [inaudible] began a
work pivotal to the development

00:18:41.020 --> 00:18:47.100
of his technique, the wood
turners of Constantinople.

00:18:47.100 --> 00:18:50.270
Even for his standard, he
did an amazing large number

00:18:50.270 --> 00:18:52.430
of preparatory studies.

00:18:52.430 --> 00:18:54.970
Even though he came ack to
the panel numerous times

00:18:54.970 --> 00:18:57.340
in the following
years, the panel started

00:18:57.340 --> 00:18:59.970
in egg tempera was
never finished.

00:18:59.970 --> 00:19:02.770
Nevertheless, the panel is
of particular importance

00:19:02.770 --> 00:19:04.880
because it shows
a new development

00:19:04.880 --> 00:19:07.080
in [inaudible] work
unlike the portraits he did

00:19:07.080 --> 00:19:12.500
for the [inaudible] museum,
the arsenal gallery of Vienna.

00:19:12.500 --> 00:19:15.920
Although his panel still shows
a scientific 3-dimensional

00:19:15.920 --> 00:19:18.990
perspective, which is not
found in the later works,

00:19:18.990 --> 00:19:20.900
the figures no longer
seem captured

00:19:20.900 --> 00:19:23.970
in a temporary situation,
but seem arrested

00:19:23.970 --> 00:19:26.470
in their movement
in a timeless space.

00:19:26.470 --> 00:19:30.080
As [inaudible] says, the work
of art, the genuine work,

00:19:30.080 --> 00:19:33.900
opens the eyes of the
beholder to see reality anew,

00:19:33.900 --> 00:19:36.000
prepared for contemplation.

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:40.300
By 1918, [inaudible] had
returned to his studio in Vienna

00:19:40.300 --> 00:19:43.000
which he would maintain
until 39.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:45.140
The [inaudible] now
had a son and daughter.

00:19:45.140 --> 00:19:47.720
Post war Austria suffered
from hunger, cold,

00:19:47.720 --> 00:19:50.140
the constant currency
devaluation

00:19:50.140 --> 00:19:52.210
and shattered self-confidence.

00:19:52.210 --> 00:19:53.510
The political situation

00:19:53.510 --> 00:19:56.150
in the young republic
was tense and uncertain.

00:19:56.150 --> 00:19:59.540
The fear of overwhelming
communism was in the air.

00:19:59.540 --> 00:20:01.440
People thought that
only an annexation

00:20:01.440 --> 00:20:04.510
by Germany could save the
situation, but it was not

00:20:04.510 --> 00:20:09.350
until 1938, until the
[inaudible] became a reality.

00:20:09.350 --> 00:20:13.800
As a result, the [inaudible]
decided to go to the country,

00:20:13.800 --> 00:20:16.450
to [inaudible], where they met
Dr. [inaudible] and his wife

00:20:16.450 --> 00:20:18.010
who helped him find lodging.

00:20:18.010 --> 00:20:20.010
[ Background noise ]

00:20:20.010 --> 00:20:21.310
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS HOLBROOK:

00:20:21.310 --> 00:20:22.610
They developed a
long-lasting friendship.

00:20:22.610 --> 00:20:25.240
[inaudible] was a passionate
Latinist, quickly attracted

00:20:25.240 --> 00:20:27.340
to the well-educated painter.

00:20:27.340 --> 00:20:28.640
They were able to store some

00:20:28.640 --> 00:20:30.910
of [inaudible] possessions
including letters,

00:20:30.910 --> 00:20:34.060
in safekeeping during
world war 2.

00:20:34.060 --> 00:20:36.830
Around 1920, the [inaudible]
family left [inaudible]

00:20:36.830 --> 00:20:41.560
at the invitation of his friend
and patron Ferdinand [inaudible]

00:20:41.560 --> 00:20:44.420
to stay at his estate in
Saint Martin in [inaudible]

00:20:44.420 --> 00:20:49.750
where they continued to
summer for a decade or so.

00:20:49.750 --> 00:20:53.070
Rudolph [inaudible], the great
German typographer, calligrapher

00:20:53.070 --> 00:20:56.730
and craftsman describes the
creative atmosphere during these

00:20:56.730 --> 00:21:01.800
months and includes what then
about victor [inaudible].

00:21:01.800 --> 00:21:03.180
Is he an artist?

00:21:03.180 --> 00:21:04.700
Is he an artisan?

00:21:04.700 --> 00:21:08.340
Neither word fits his case as
both are linked to concepts

00:21:08.340 --> 00:21:10.200
which are refuted by him.

00:21:10.200 --> 00:21:12.720
He is not a combination
of both either.

00:21:12.720 --> 00:21:16.350
It is better to say that
he is neither of the 2.

00:21:16.350 --> 00:21:18.890
For an artist, he is
too practically minded,

00:21:18.890 --> 00:21:20.760
to sober, to normal.

00:21:20.760 --> 00:21:23.760
There is nothing fanciful
or exalted about him.

00:21:23.760 --> 00:21:26.380
For a craftsman, his
mind is too profound,

00:21:26.380 --> 00:21:28.990
his intellectual
measure to great.

00:21:28.990 --> 00:21:33.490
As early as 1910, [inaudible]
had been experimenting

00:21:33.490 --> 00:21:35.000
with the technique
of the [inaudible],

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:39.400
and almost forgotten
discipling which his concern

00:21:39.400 --> 00:21:40.880
for graphic preciseness,

00:21:40.880 --> 00:21:43.920
proved to be an ideal
medium for the artist.

00:21:43.920 --> 00:21:46.540
The technique had been widely
used for copying paintings

00:21:46.540 --> 00:21:50.450
from the late 18th into the
second half of the 19th century,

00:21:50.450 --> 00:21:53.370
especially in England
and in Austria.

00:21:53.370 --> 00:21:56.370
In Saint Martin,
[inaudible] returned to it,

00:21:56.370 --> 00:21:58.680
finishing the portrait of
[inaudible] depicting him

00:21:58.680 --> 00:22:04.640
in a traditional
Austrian hunting outfit.

00:22:04.640 --> 00:22:06.420
He later did a number
of illustrations

00:22:06.420 --> 00:22:10.620
of traditional Austrian clothing
known as trachten for his friend

00:22:10.620 --> 00:22:11.920
and patron, Conrad [inaudible].

00:22:11.920 --> 00:22:17.230
In 1924, he extended his
skill in London where the arts

00:22:17.230 --> 00:22:19.020
of the [inaudible]
was still taught

00:22:19.020 --> 00:22:21.320
at the royal college of art.

00:22:21.320 --> 00:22:22.970
Thereafter, he completed
a number

00:22:22.970 --> 00:22:26.520
of [inaudible] including
a portrait

00:22:26.520 --> 00:22:30.860
of [inaudible] government
head, Dr. Carl Maria Stephen,

00:22:30.860 --> 00:22:32.830
pictured there in the hat,

00:22:32.830 --> 00:22:36.430
Viennese operetta star
[inaudible] again,

00:22:36.430 --> 00:22:39.360
although not here as
Madam [inaudible],

00:22:39.360 --> 00:22:45.330
[inaudible] patrician of Baron
of whom he also made a portrait

00:22:45.330 --> 00:22:48.510
in oil and tempera in 1924.

00:22:48.510 --> 00:22:50.900
Victor von [inaudible],
professor of folklore

00:22:50.900 --> 00:22:55.540
at the university of Graz,
Martha [inaudible] as well

00:22:55.540 --> 00:22:59.290
as his friend, the
musicologist [inaudible] who is

00:22:59.290 --> 00:23:02.710
down in the lower left
corner with whom he carried

00:23:02.710 --> 00:23:06.470
on an extensive correspondence
about the parallel relationship

00:23:06.470 --> 00:23:10.450
of form and structure in
music and the visual arts.

00:23:10.450 --> 00:23:13.490
His own [inaudible]
self-portrait here

00:23:13.490 --> 00:23:15.200
with the glasses and looking

00:23:15.200 --> 00:23:19.390
over his shoulder
was complete in 1926.

00:23:19.390 --> 00:23:21.890
The year 1922 marks
the beginning

00:23:21.890 --> 00:23:25.040
of victor's most productive
period as an artist

00:23:25.040 --> 00:23:28.980
which sees the crystallization
of his mature painting style.

00:23:28.980 --> 00:23:31.200
The creation of his
first [inaudible] faces

00:23:31.200 --> 00:23:34.730
and the establishment
of his printing press.

00:23:34.730 --> 00:23:37.840
This is a version, an
early version, of Christ

00:23:37.840 --> 00:23:40.310
and the adulteress, an image

00:23:40.310 --> 00:23:44.940
which he painted 5 different
times over a long period

00:23:44.940 --> 00:23:51.330
of years and our thinking
about it is he meditated

00:23:51.330 --> 00:23:55.200
on [inaudible] suicide because
of Maria von [inaudible]

00:23:55.200 --> 00:24:04.450
adultery and it was a way of
dealing with that tragedy.

00:24:04.450 --> 00:24:08.420
Victor returned to Florence with
his family and set up his studio

00:24:08.420 --> 00:24:11.480
and household in
October of 1922,

00:24:11.480 --> 00:24:18.730
at first at the Villa
[inaudible] in Sophiono then

00:24:18.730 --> 00:24:20.120
in the [inaudible]
in [inaudible]

00:24:20.120 --> 00:24:22.560
where he became a neighbor
to Baroner [inaudible].

00:24:22.560 --> 00:24:27.320
It was with the crystallization
of this mature style

00:24:27.320 --> 00:24:30.070
in the portrait of
Madam [inaudible] shown

00:24:30.070 --> 00:24:37.010
at the Venetian [inaudible] of
1924 with, and his own portrait

00:24:37.010 --> 00:24:40.700
with Lute [inaudible] and
tuning fork and the portrait

00:24:40.700 --> 00:24:42.190
of [inaudible], the
court of saint James,

00:24:42.190 --> 00:24:46.570
that [inaudible] had
a realization crucial

00:24:46.570 --> 00:24:48.340
to his self-understanding.

00:24:48.340 --> 00:24:50.650
I just wanted to
point out the portrait

00:24:50.650 --> 00:24:56.570
of the Swiss Madam
[inaudible] and the difference

00:24:56.570 --> 00:25:01.110
in a color version and a
black and white version.

00:25:01.110 --> 00:25:05.720
Victor always painted something
new in each of his portraits

00:25:05.720 --> 00:25:08.390
and he was interested in
learning to paint a glass

00:25:08.390 --> 00:25:13.080
or in this one which is
suspended on the chain along

00:25:13.080 --> 00:25:21.310
which also you find his
printer's mark suspended

00:25:21.310 --> 00:25:22.610
from the end of a chain.

00:25:22.610 --> 00:25:26.260
It is a very interesting
medieval allegory going

00:25:26.260 --> 00:25:30.190
on in the background in the,
and in the middle ground

00:25:30.190 --> 00:25:34.770
with people doing
various things over here

00:25:34.770 --> 00:25:39.480
and very interestingly,
Franciscan monk, a Jesuit,

00:25:39.480 --> 00:25:48.840
I mean [inaudible], a figure, a
Christ like figure dangling down

00:25:48.840 --> 00:25:53.510
and the adulteress
appearing once again.

00:25:53.510 --> 00:25:59.350
[ Background noise ]

00:25:59.350 --> 00:26:00.840
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS HOLBROOK:
Back to [inaudible].

00:26:00.840 --> 00:26:04.780
As a child, [inaudible]
had looked

00:26:04.780 --> 00:26:08.330
out of his bedroom window
one morning and writes,

00:26:08.330 --> 00:26:11.680
at one glass I absorbed all
the forms in front of me.

00:26:11.680 --> 00:26:15.360
Their order, the contrast of
light and shadow, warm and cool

00:26:15.360 --> 00:26:18.600
as it were, and the
relationship of planes.

00:26:18.600 --> 00:26:21.440
I also saw the narrow street
coming from the left-hand side

00:26:21.440 --> 00:26:24.040
and broadening into
the narrow square.

00:26:24.040 --> 00:26:25.600
Through the open door
of the gate house,

00:26:25.600 --> 00:26:27.090
I could see the sunlight

00:26:27.090 --> 00:26:30.350
on the distant pavement
of the [inaudible].

00:26:30.350 --> 00:26:33.080
The tiny belfry with its
cross on top stood clear

00:26:33.080 --> 00:26:35.530
against a transparent sky.

00:26:35.530 --> 00:26:38.310
Yellow sunlight already lay on
the roofs and the upper part

00:26:38.310 --> 00:26:40.430
of the house walls while cool,

00:26:40.430 --> 00:26:43.790
gray shade still filled
the narrow street.

00:26:43.790 --> 00:26:47.410
Horizontal and vertical forms,
rough and smooth surfaces,

00:26:47.410 --> 00:26:52.610
solid, tangible forms against
the sky, that was all there was,

00:26:52.610 --> 00:26:55.770
nothing poetical, nothing
emotional, no yearning,

00:26:55.770 --> 00:26:58.350
no great distance,
nothing idyllic.

00:26:58.350 --> 00:27:01.800
Only quiet, clear
sensitively arranged forms.

00:27:01.800 --> 00:27:05.490
After a short while, I left the
window and picked up the shreds

00:27:05.490 --> 00:27:09.660
of a child's life where I
have left off the day before.

00:27:09.660 --> 00:27:12.220
Many years passed and I was
nearing the middle of life.

00:27:12.220 --> 00:27:15.750
I had forgotten what I
had seen as a little oy.

00:27:15.750 --> 00:27:17.980
Sometimes at long
intervals, a recollection

00:27:17.980 --> 00:27:20.600
of those moments
flash through my mind.

00:27:20.600 --> 00:27:22.350
It soothed me while it lasted,

00:27:22.350 --> 00:27:25.590
but no longer did it
mean anything to me.

00:27:25.590 --> 00:27:27.260
When I was in London,
I was commissioned

00:27:27.260 --> 00:27:29.950
by the Swiss minister to
the court of Saint James

00:27:29.950 --> 00:27:31.530
to paint his portrait.

00:27:31.530 --> 00:27:35.140
I made all his studies in London
then went back to Florence

00:27:35.140 --> 00:27:37.150
to paint the panel there.

00:27:37.150 --> 00:27:39.830
As Mr. [inaudible] was in
the garb of a minister,

00:27:39.830 --> 00:27:42.440
I had a chosen a view of
the ambassador's court

00:27:42.440 --> 00:27:44.440
in the Saint James palace

00:27:44.440 --> 00:27:47.160
with a little white
tower as a background.

00:27:47.160 --> 00:27:50.580
After I finished the painting,
I took it to London for delivery

00:27:50.580 --> 00:27:53.060
and should it be necessary,
to give it final touches

00:27:53.060 --> 00:27:55.390
in the presence of the model.

00:27:55.390 --> 00:27:58.150
When I took it out of the box
and saw it with fresh eyes,

00:27:58.150 --> 00:28:00.500
the recollection of what
I'd seen from the window

00:28:00.500 --> 00:28:02.910
as a little boy came
back to me suddenly

00:28:02.910 --> 00:28:05.380
and was more vivid
than ever before.

00:28:05.380 --> 00:28:08.840
I realized that I had repeated
that scene in the painting,

00:28:08.840 --> 00:28:11.700
horizontal plane alternating
with vertical ones,

00:28:11.700 --> 00:28:15.190
quiet and moving masses,
clear and tangible forms

00:28:15.190 --> 00:28:19.890
against a sky, a London sky,
gray and murky, in my portrait.

00:28:19.890 --> 00:28:22.400
The tiny belfry, the
[inaudible] in the street,

00:28:22.400 --> 00:28:26.600
everything was there, oddly
changed yet recognizable.

00:28:26.600 --> 00:28:29.620
Even myself in the
person of the model.

00:28:29.620 --> 00:28:32.030
Mentally, I reviewed
my past work.

00:28:32.030 --> 00:28:34.420
I was both agitated and puzzled.

00:28:34.420 --> 00:28:37.800
No doubt, here was a pattern
of composition which recurred

00:28:37.800 --> 00:28:42.420
in all my work however disguised
in each particular one.

00:28:42.420 --> 00:28:44.750
The subject matter had
no influence upon it,

00:28:44.750 --> 00:28:48.380
whether a portrait, a historical
scene or a single figure,

00:28:48.380 --> 00:28:51.340
I had cast it in the same mold.

00:28:51.340 --> 00:28:56.520
The 3 latest large
self-portraits provide

00:28:56.520 --> 00:29:00.210
understandable examples of this.

00:29:00.210 --> 00:29:06.800
Not including, the 2
large ones with paintbrush

00:29:06.800 --> 00:29:09.510
in one hand, different hands.

00:29:09.510 --> 00:29:14.010
[ Background noise ]

00:29:14.010 --> 00:29:15.310
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS HOLBROOK:

00:29:15.310 --> 00:29:16.610
Everything must be
comprehensible,

00:29:16.610 --> 00:29:19.390
the depth clearly readable in
all parts of the depiction.

00:29:19.390 --> 00:29:22.270
The occasion for the
picture is hardly thought of.

00:29:22.270 --> 00:29:23.960
Since it is a portrait,
we do not want

00:29:23.960 --> 00:29:26.330
to neglect the resemblance,

00:29:26.330 --> 00:29:29.810
but it is only 1
requirement among many.

00:29:29.810 --> 00:29:33.030
Clothing, objects, background
are chosen according to points

00:29:33.030 --> 00:29:36.610
of view differing from those
thought of by the client

00:29:36.610 --> 00:29:39.710
or by those later
perceived by the critics.

00:29:39.710 --> 00:29:43.040
Everything is created to be
mutually interchangeable.

00:29:43.040 --> 00:29:46.370
The characteristics of the live
image are carefully explored

00:29:46.370 --> 00:29:48.820
in the many preparatory studies.

00:29:48.820 --> 00:29:50.860
His individuality is
the starting point

00:29:50.860 --> 00:29:54.680
of the construction, but the
construction is always the same.

00:29:54.680 --> 00:29:57.230
We always seek to create the
same work of art according

00:29:57.230 --> 00:29:59.260
to the same law and each time,

00:29:59.260 --> 00:30:03.360
only its outward
appearance varies.

00:30:03.360 --> 00:30:04.660
[inaudible].

00:30:04.660 --> 00:30:08.820
Always the same, but
not in the same way.

00:30:08.820 --> 00:30:12.200
Invoking the memory of
[inaudible] with whom

00:30:12.200 --> 00:30:13.990
in their long correspondence,

00:30:13.990 --> 00:30:16.990
there was so much
cross fertilization.

00:30:18.880 --> 00:30:20.180
The book sellers

00:30:20.180 --> 00:30:23.170
at the [inaudible] shows
perfectly an example

00:30:23.170 --> 00:30:27.380
of the form, the geometry, to
which [inaudible] is essential,

00:30:27.380 --> 00:30:30.090
refers as essential
to his compositions.

00:30:30.090 --> 00:30:31.660
That underlying structure,

00:30:31.660 --> 00:30:34.680
the remnant of his
childhood impressions.

00:30:34.680 --> 00:30:38.800
Here is a triangle form by
the man pointing and speaking.

00:30:38.800 --> 00:30:41.840
His head at the vertex
and the seated men turning

00:30:41.840 --> 00:30:43.530
on the stool to listen.

00:30:43.530 --> 00:30:45.780
The background is
skillfully arranged

00:30:45.780 --> 00:30:47.960
to distract the eye
from the triangle.

00:30:47.960 --> 00:30:50.450
The subjects are
arranged within the frame

00:30:50.450 --> 00:30:54.290
on 3 independent planes,
foreground, middle plane

00:30:54.290 --> 00:30:57.510
and background, all
resting on the ground plan.

00:30:57.510 --> 00:31:01.790
[ Background noise ]

00:31:01.790 --> 00:31:05.040
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS HOLBROOK: This
later version of the adulteress.

00:31:05.040 --> 00:31:08.040
[inaudible] uses overlapping
forms to create space

00:31:08.040 --> 00:31:10.160
as the medieval painters did.

00:31:10.160 --> 00:31:12.830
The fact that parts of a
whole are nearer to or farther

00:31:12.830 --> 00:31:14.740
from the eye, that when falling

00:31:14.740 --> 00:31:17.330
on one side they must
rise on the other.

00:31:17.330 --> 00:31:19.580
In fact, that all this
happens within the framework

00:31:19.580 --> 00:31:23.500
of foreground and background
and on a definite ground plan.

00:31:23.500 --> 00:31:27.750
This is the whole content
of classic work of art.

00:31:27.750 --> 00:31:32.170
To shape these events with
his hands is the true,

00:31:32.170 --> 00:31:35.870
is to the true artist an
ever novel, never repeated,

00:31:35.870 --> 00:31:38.430
always the same pure task.

00:31:38.430 --> 00:31:41.860
It is what was accomplished
in the medieval workshop.

00:31:41.860 --> 00:31:44.460
As he says, the medieval
artist was observant

00:31:44.460 --> 00:31:46.300
of the rules of his craft.

00:31:46.300 --> 00:31:48.200
The rules were not arbitrary.

00:31:48.200 --> 00:31:49.930
They were not setup
for the convenience

00:31:49.930 --> 00:31:52.200
of either the artist
or the patron.

00:31:52.200 --> 00:31:54.570
When followed, these
rules attained an end,

00:31:54.570 --> 00:31:56.690
a work of civilized art to fit

00:31:56.690 --> 00:31:59.490
into a civilized
people's environment.

00:31:59.490 --> 00:32:01.950
The patron was not
interested in the rules,

00:32:01.950 --> 00:32:05.750
but in the end obtained what
[inaudible] ready to pay.

00:32:05.750 --> 00:32:08.680
If he ordered an image
of Saint Sebastian,

00:32:08.680 --> 00:32:10.060
he expected to get a picture

00:32:10.060 --> 00:32:12.760
of a naked young man
spiked with arrows.

00:32:12.760 --> 00:32:15.620
It was easy for the
artist to comply with this,

00:32:15.620 --> 00:32:16.940
but to observe the rules

00:32:16.940 --> 00:32:19.790
of the workshop was
quite a different thing.

00:32:19.790 --> 00:32:22.800
Without it being laid
down expressly as a rule,

00:32:22.800 --> 00:32:26.580
the concern for the workshop
was to make the saint visible,

00:32:26.580 --> 00:32:28.770
visible to the beholder.

00:32:28.770 --> 00:32:31.880
This was not a matter of
observation of nature,

00:32:31.880 --> 00:32:34.540
of scientific watching
and scrutinizing,

00:32:34.540 --> 00:32:38.570
nor was it a matter of
making concepts visible.

00:32:38.570 --> 00:32:40.960
An old man with a white
beard and a halo served

00:32:40.960 --> 00:32:43.780
for god the father and
human beings with wings

00:32:43.780 --> 00:32:46.030
on their shoulders
served for angels.

00:32:46.030 --> 00:32:49.420
The devil was always at
the bottom, never on top.

00:32:49.420 --> 00:32:52.730
In modern terminology,
this was show business

00:32:52.730 --> 00:32:56.190
and show people know what
affects an audience visually.

00:32:56.190 --> 00:32:59.750
The medieval craftsman
knew it to.

00:32:59.750 --> 00:33:03.220
[inaudible] was able to work out
his personal type of classic art

00:33:03.220 --> 00:33:06.710
and to create a portrait style
valid for the rest of his life,

00:33:06.710 --> 00:33:09.330
a development showing
its first visual outburst

00:33:09.330 --> 00:33:12.330
in the timelessness
and graphic quality

00:33:12.330 --> 00:33:16.330
of the wood turners of 1918.

00:33:16.330 --> 00:33:19.630
The time in Florence from
1924 to 29 were a time

00:33:19.630 --> 00:33:21.370
of serenity for [inaudible].

00:33:21.370 --> 00:33:24.870
He completed numerous portraits
in [inaudible], Berlin, Munich,

00:33:24.870 --> 00:33:28.840
Paris, [inaudible], London,
Strasburg and in Pittsburgh,

00:33:28.840 --> 00:33:31.530
for his Patron Edgar
[inaudible].

00:33:31.530 --> 00:33:34.390
He began cutting [inaudible],

00:33:34.390 --> 00:33:38.080
setting up his printing
in [inaudible].

00:33:38.080 --> 00:33:41.820
He also built together with
[inaudible] a carpenter,

00:33:41.820 --> 00:33:45.050
2 clavichords as
prototypes for kids.

00:33:45.050 --> 00:33:47.670
Albert [inaudible] had suggested
this idea to [inaudible]

00:33:47.670 --> 00:33:49.300
since both were great components

00:33:49.300 --> 00:33:52.050
of the clavichord
and the harpsichord.

00:33:52.050 --> 00:33:54.630
Unfortunately, we will
probably never know the details

00:33:54.630 --> 00:33:58.140
of this project because prior
to their departure from Vienna,

00:33:58.140 --> 00:34:00.510
following the German
annexation in 1939, [inaudible]

00:34:00.510 --> 00:34:04.200
and his wife Rosa burned a
number of letters in order

00:34:04.200 --> 00:34:06.210
to protect their correspondence

00:34:06.210 --> 00:34:10.170
after they had left Austria
including those of [inaudible].

00:34:11.190 --> 00:34:13.440
In her book, 40 years
with [inaudible],

00:34:13.440 --> 00:34:16.510
Nikki [inaudible] wrote,
[inaudible] had been introduced

00:34:16.510 --> 00:34:20.950
to the Berenson's by one of
BB's old Austrian friends,

00:34:20.950 --> 00:34:24.330
the collector Count
Lens [inaudible].

00:34:24.330 --> 00:34:26.110
[inaudible] seemed to
belong to another century

00:34:26.110 --> 00:34:28.760
in combining art
and artisanship.

00:34:28.760 --> 00:34:31.240
An accomplished painter,
a printer of fine books,

00:34:31.240 --> 00:34:34.530
a constructor of musical
instruments, his discussion

00:34:34.530 --> 00:34:37.990
with Bb were sometimes
so profound and involved

00:34:37.990 --> 00:34:41.650
that ordinary mortals
could not follow them.

00:34:41.650 --> 00:34:43.750
Berenson was not
sympathetic to [inaudible]

00:34:43.750 --> 00:34:47.200
at this time nor
ever, yet the family

00:34:47.200 --> 00:34:50.760
and Nikki [inaudible] were
always the kindest of friends.

00:34:50.760 --> 00:34:55.240
As [inaudible] himself records,

00:34:55.240 --> 00:34:56.850
when I had finished
the self-portrait

00:34:56.850 --> 00:34:59.300
with the tuning fork
which is usually mistaken

00:34:59.300 --> 00:35:02.260
as a fever thermometer
at first sight,

00:35:02.260 --> 00:35:05.500
dear kind Nikki [inaudible]
wanted me to show it to Berenson

00:35:05.500 --> 00:35:08.690
for she liked it and she
said he might be interested

00:35:08.690 --> 00:35:10.480
in seeing it.

00:35:10.480 --> 00:35:12.360
I took the picture one
day over to [inaudible],

00:35:12.360 --> 00:35:16.440
setting it in a chair
in Berenson's study.

00:35:16.440 --> 00:35:18.850
What he said I do
not recall in full,

00:35:18.850 --> 00:35:22.080
only one thing I remember
well, he said it looks like one

00:35:22.080 --> 00:35:26.360
of those wooden painted statues
one sees in Spain on the altars

00:35:26.360 --> 00:35:30.260
of churches and this
was and is true.

00:35:30.260 --> 00:35:33.700
I did not take this criticism
as a complement at that time

00:35:33.700 --> 00:35:38.730
and Berenson did not mean
it to be one, but now I see

00:35:38.730 --> 00:35:41.300
that Berenson's judgement
was in a sense,

00:35:41.300 --> 00:35:44.100
rather an involuntary
compliment.

00:35:44.100 --> 00:35:47.260
For some argument, he pointed
to the Madonna of [inaudible]

00:35:47.260 --> 00:35:50.540
that hung in the study
next to the window.

00:35:50.540 --> 00:35:52.710
I saw immediately
the weak part in it

00:35:52.710 --> 00:35:56.780
and said certainly not too
politely, but how can you stand

00:35:56.780 --> 00:35:59.780
that left side of the mantle
falling down into nothing

00:35:59.780 --> 00:36:02.680
against the firm
triangle of the child.

00:36:02.680 --> 00:36:05.490
For a while he was
silent, realizing perhaps

00:36:05.490 --> 00:36:06.850
for the first time that the bulk

00:36:06.850 --> 00:36:09.110
of the child was not
counterbalanced by anything

00:36:09.110 --> 00:36:12.040
on the opposite, the
left side, by anything

00:36:12.040 --> 00:36:14.450
but the weak part of the mantle.

00:36:14.450 --> 00:36:19.780
Then he continued, yes, I admit
this but what about the rest?

00:36:19.780 --> 00:36:22.120
The question itself
was a wrong one.

00:36:22.120 --> 00:36:24.480
If something in the whole
composition is wrong,

00:36:24.480 --> 00:36:27.180
there is nothing left
for being any good.

00:36:27.180 --> 00:36:31.700
Lovely though the child
is and the mother too.

00:36:31.700 --> 00:36:35.640
Among musicians in Florence,
[inaudible] knew Adolf Bush

00:36:35.640 --> 00:36:38.390
and Rudolph [inaudible]
who years later came

00:36:38.390 --> 00:36:41.660
to see [inaudible] in
Lexington on 2 occasions.

00:36:41.660 --> 00:36:44.560
He had bought the drawing
for the portrait of,

00:36:44.560 --> 00:36:45.860
Victor's portrait of
Thomas [inaudible].

00:36:45.860 --> 00:36:49.700
Through his Munich patrons the
[inaudible], he was introduced

00:36:49.700 --> 00:36:53.360
to Carlo [inaudible], a
Florentine noble, novelist,

00:36:53.360 --> 00:36:56.510
travel writer and figure
in the local literary life,

00:36:56.510 --> 00:36:59.500
art collector [inaudible]
and lawyer

00:36:59.500 --> 00:37:02.910
and American art
collector Carlo [inaudible].

00:37:02.910 --> 00:37:04.210
Ulrich [inaudible], head

00:37:04.210 --> 00:37:06.790
of the German art
institute, became a friend.

00:37:06.790 --> 00:37:09.690
They would be reunited in
Chicago where [inaudible],

00:37:09.690 --> 00:37:11.700
formerly head of the art
department at the University

00:37:11.700 --> 00:37:14.320
of Chicago, arranged
an exhibition

00:37:14.320 --> 00:37:17.690
for [inaudible] in 1948.

00:37:17.690 --> 00:37:21.560
Through the Berenson, he met Sir
John Rosenstein whose wife was

00:37:21.560 --> 00:37:24.250
from Lexington, Kentucky
and Kenneth Clark

00:37:24.250 --> 00:37:26.630
who became a patron and friend.

00:37:26.630 --> 00:37:30.860
Edward Ned Bruce, also an artist
and later in charge of the WPA

00:37:30.860 --> 00:37:33.710
at the treasury department
was a kind friend

00:37:33.710 --> 00:37:36.140
who brought his friends
to meet [inaudible],

00:37:36.140 --> 00:37:39.580
among whom was [inaudible]
Huxley whose philosophy

00:37:39.580 --> 00:37:41.200
[inaudible] admired.

00:37:41.200 --> 00:37:43.620
Huxley saw [inaudible] many
years later in Lexington

00:37:43.620 --> 00:37:46.510
when he lectured at
Transylvania University.

00:37:46.510 --> 00:37:51.260
[ Background noise ]

00:37:51.260 --> 00:37:52.560
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS HOLBROOK:
[inaudible] drawings

00:37:52.560 --> 00:37:57.230
of [inaudible] and
of Mary Berenson,

00:37:57.230 --> 00:38:00.200
fine and firm images much work

00:38:00.200 --> 00:38:02.850
over are almost speaking
images [inaudible].

00:38:02.850 --> 00:38:07.240
[inaudible] writes of
another similar drawing

00:38:07.240 --> 00:38:08.540
of Sir Frederick [inaudible].

00:38:08.540 --> 00:38:12.890
In the early 1920's,

00:38:12.890 --> 00:38:17.560
the Austrian minister Baron
[inaudible] invited him to come

00:38:17.560 --> 00:38:20.620
to London and stay with him
at the embassy while I worked

00:38:20.620 --> 00:38:22.750
on the drawing for his portrait.

00:38:22.750 --> 00:38:24.590
He decided I should
make a drawing of one

00:38:24.590 --> 00:38:25.900
of his acquaintances,

00:38:25.900 --> 00:38:28.990
a very distinguished
looking gentleman at court.

00:38:28.990 --> 00:38:32.340
This night, as we both
innocently believed result

00:38:32.340 --> 00:38:35.840
in other conditions when
the drawing would be seen.

00:38:35.840 --> 00:38:39.230
So, I made the drawing which
I recall was a silver point.

00:38:39.230 --> 00:38:41.020
Sir Frederick accepted
it gracefully

00:38:41.020 --> 00:38:44.200
and hoped its display
would be a success.

00:38:44.200 --> 00:38:45.500
After a long while,

00:38:45.500 --> 00:38:47.770
Baron [inaudible] asked
whether the drawing had

00:38:47.770 --> 00:38:49.220
been appreciated.

00:38:49.220 --> 00:38:52.920
Sir Frederick's reply was
that it may have been,

00:38:52.920 --> 00:38:54.690
but though he could
lead horses to water,

00:38:54.690 --> 00:38:57.150
he couldn't make them drink.

00:38:57.150 --> 00:38:58.680
Years later in Lexington,

00:38:58.680 --> 00:39:00.900
our good neighbor Mary
[inaudible] came one day

00:39:00.900 --> 00:39:04.490
with a book for me, grace
and favor, the memoires

00:39:04.490 --> 00:39:06.840
of the duchess of West Minster.

00:39:06.840 --> 00:39:10.080
In this book was the drawing
I had made of her father.

00:39:10.080 --> 00:39:13.170
His face had, she
said, the refinement

00:39:13.170 --> 00:39:14.580
of a [inaudible] drawing.

00:39:14.580 --> 00:39:17.070
She seems to have seen
him through my eyes

00:39:17.070 --> 00:39:19.790
for my drawing had
the characteristics

00:39:19.790 --> 00:39:22.930
of a [inaudible] drawing though
I did not have the benefit

00:39:22.930 --> 00:39:24.800
of renaissance dress.

00:39:24.800 --> 00:39:28.310
[inaudible] had been
interested in the book arts

00:39:28.310 --> 00:39:31.710
since he began book binding
in 1911, hoping one day

00:39:31.710 --> 00:39:33.910
to print and bind a book.

00:39:33.910 --> 00:39:35.320
In Florence, he experimented

00:39:35.320 --> 00:39:38.780
with cutting type eventually
created several [inaudible]

00:39:38.780 --> 00:39:44.040
faces, the first being cut
in 1921 by Swiss type cutter.

00:39:44.040 --> 00:39:47.370
1926, [inaudible]
and [inaudible],

00:39:47.370 --> 00:39:48.720
son of Rudolph [inaudible],

00:39:48.720 --> 00:39:51.640
began cutting a second
type face together.

00:39:51.640 --> 00:39:54.560
It was cast by hand
in the studio in 1928

00:39:54.560 --> 00:39:57.900
and would be called [inaudible]
after the first issue

00:39:57.900 --> 00:40:03.310
from the press in 1931 and that
book is the second from the end

00:40:03.310 --> 00:40:07.850
of the left side of the table.

00:40:07.850 --> 00:40:11.370
Deciding that if he were
creating a type face

00:40:11.370 --> 00:40:12.880
and using handmade paper,

00:40:12.880 --> 00:40:15.670
he should also have a
handmade printing press.

00:40:15.670 --> 00:40:19.040
In 1927, [inaudible] made some
drawings of a wooden press

00:40:19.040 --> 00:40:23.280
in the bibliotheca [inaudible].

00:40:23.280 --> 00:40:25.740
While still living
in the [inaudible],

00:40:25.740 --> 00:40:29.640
his craftsman friend,
built the press.

00:40:29.640 --> 00:40:32.140
Neighbor [inaudible] Berenson
suggested that in [inaudible],

00:40:32.140 --> 00:40:33.840
appropriate first issue

00:40:33.840 --> 00:40:39.370
of the press might be John
Milton's Samson Agonistes

00:40:39.370 --> 00:40:43.670
for reasons unclear, but
that was the suggestion

00:40:43.670 --> 00:40:45.720
and it was accepted.

00:40:45.720 --> 00:40:49.300
At a luncheon party in 1929,

00:40:49.300 --> 00:40:50.600
[inaudible] had a
fortuitous meeting

00:40:50.600 --> 00:40:52.490
with Edgar [inaudible]
sr. at Pittsburgh.

00:40:52.490 --> 00:40:53.790
[inaudible] had completed
a drawing

00:40:53.790 --> 00:40:57.110
of his wife Lilly Ann in 1926.

00:40:57.110 --> 00:40:59.740
[inaudible] asked [inaudible]
if he would come to Pittsburgh

00:40:59.740 --> 00:41:02.060
to paint several portraits.

00:41:02.060 --> 00:41:04.180
[inaudible] thus made his
first visit to the U.S

00:41:04.180 --> 00:41:08.500
for commissions including
Edgar [inaudible] portrait

00:41:08.500 --> 00:41:13.280
which now hangs in the
dining room at Falling Water.

00:41:13.280 --> 00:41:15.870
[inaudible] became interested
in the printing project,

00:41:15.870 --> 00:41:18.300
decided to support the
effort allowing [inaudible]

00:41:18.300 --> 00:41:21.490
to build a second press
and asked [inaudible]

00:41:21.490 --> 00:41:25.320
with Mrs. [inaudible] urging
to take their son, Edgar Jr.,

00:41:25.320 --> 00:41:28.290
on as an apprentice
in his art studio.

00:41:28.290 --> 00:41:32.420
In addition to [inaudible] the
studio included Fritz Cradle

00:41:32.420 --> 00:41:35.110
who had been a student
of Rudolph [inaudible],

00:41:35.110 --> 00:41:36.920
Fritz Arnold from
the [inaudible] house

00:41:36.920 --> 00:41:38.890
and young [inaudible].

00:41:38.890 --> 00:41:42.320
Then in later 1929, with a
need for larger quarters,

00:41:42.320 --> 00:41:45.520
the [inaudible] moved to
a villa in [inaudible],

00:41:45.520 --> 00:41:48.740
on the south side
of the [inaudible].

00:41:48.740 --> 00:41:52.740
The press finally completed
and the printing finally done,

00:41:52.740 --> 00:41:57.270
was named the [inaudible]
because a worn

00:41:57.270 --> 00:41:59.770
and nameless statue of a
little saint in a niche

00:41:59.770 --> 00:42:02.690
by the villa's entrance
was the little [inaudible]

00:42:02.690 --> 00:42:06.950
and the photograph, one of the
photographs there on the right

00:42:06.950 --> 00:42:10.810
of the tale show the niche.

00:42:10.810 --> 00:42:14.230
In addition to spending some of
the summer at count [inaudible],

00:42:14.230 --> 00:42:16.700
the family also came
to the summer home

00:42:16.700 --> 00:42:18.580
of the [inaudible] family.

00:42:18.580 --> 00:42:21.300
Conrad [inaudible], scion of
an Austrian industrial family,

00:42:21.300 --> 00:42:22.810
spent most of his
time in [inaudible],

00:42:22.810 --> 00:42:27.210
one of the small Austrian lakes
in the western [inaudible] area

00:42:27.210 --> 00:42:30.750
where many Viennese
families summered.

00:42:30.750 --> 00:42:33.700
[inaudible] was a collector of
steerian folk sounds and dances

00:42:33.700 --> 00:42:37.340
and a [inaudible] expert on
the dialect of this region.

00:42:37.340 --> 00:42:41.060
Here, [inaudible] met numerous
friends including Austrian

00:42:41.060 --> 00:42:46.870
dramatist and poet Hugo von
[inaudible], the Frankenstein's,

00:42:46.870 --> 00:42:51.080
and Gabrielle von [inaudible]
who, at whose [inaudible],

00:42:51.080 --> 00:42:54.890
wrote his important works.

00:42:54.890 --> 00:42:56.210
[inaudible] daughter, Veronica,

00:42:56.210 --> 00:42:58.580
would later marry the
Baron [inaudible],

00:42:58.580 --> 00:43:01.310
grandson of Gabrielle.

00:43:01.310 --> 00:43:03.810
At [inaudible], worked
on temperate paintings

00:43:03.810 --> 00:43:06.350
on parchment depicting
Austrian peasants

00:43:06.350 --> 00:43:08.460
in traditional costumes.

00:43:08.460 --> 00:43:11.790
[inaudible] shared with
[inaudible] and [inaudible],

00:43:11.790 --> 00:43:18.720
his interest in folklore
and local customs and many

00:43:18.720 --> 00:43:22.510
of his friends from the area
posed for these paintings.

00:43:22.510 --> 00:43:30.610
[ Background noise ]

00:43:30.610 --> 00:43:32.560
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS HOLBROOK:
Other paintings completed

00:43:32.560 --> 00:43:36.320
in these years were those
of Baron [inaudible]

00:43:36.320 --> 00:43:42.690
with the [inaudible]
in the background.

00:43:42.690 --> 00:43:46.460
Francesca [inaudible],
the wife of his friend

00:43:46.460 --> 00:43:50.490
and pet Delfino [inaudible] and
[inaudible], the wife of well,

00:43:50.490 --> 00:43:57.530
his friend as well as the
wife of his friend Alexander.

00:43:57.530 --> 00:44:00.190
In all these, in addition
to perfect finish obtained

00:44:00.190 --> 00:44:03.580
by the use of temper,
there is another attribute.

00:44:06.050 --> 00:44:09.860
It is the brush or the
tuning fork in the hands

00:44:09.860 --> 00:44:13.340
of the painter, the decorative
medallion in the portrait

00:44:13.340 --> 00:44:19.480
of [inaudible], the geometric
pendant in the, on the chain

00:44:19.480 --> 00:44:24.490
of Madam [inaudible] glass orb
or the twigs of an olive branch

00:44:24.490 --> 00:44:27.210
at the side of the
Austrian ambassador.

00:44:27.210 --> 00:44:30.750
All these attributes are not
merely aesthetic embellishments,

00:44:30.750 --> 00:44:34.530
but symbolic forms ornamenting
the work with increased meaning

00:44:34.530 --> 00:44:37.070
and binding it into
a visible whole.

00:44:37.070 --> 00:44:43.040
In 1932, Rosa [inaudible] and
children returned to Vienna

00:44:43.040 --> 00:44:44.680
and [inaudible] returned to
London where he had hoped

00:44:44.680 --> 00:44:47.880
to get further commissions
from friends of Kenneth Clark,

00:44:47.880 --> 00:44:50.890
[inaudible] and Frankenstein.

00:44:50.890 --> 00:44:53.160
[inaudible] completed
several [inaudible] portraits

00:44:53.160 --> 00:44:55.010
and works in silver point.

00:44:55.010 --> 00:44:57.310
He was commissioned
by a committee headed

00:44:57.310 --> 00:45:02.490
by Baron Frankenstein to create
a bronze memorial bust for,

00:45:02.490 --> 00:45:06.690
in honor of [inaudible] and to
cut a marble inscription for it,

00:45:06.690 --> 00:45:10.140
placing it in the
[inaudible] house in Salzburg,

00:45:10.140 --> 00:45:13.820
later destroyed by the Nazis.

00:45:13.820 --> 00:45:16.550
He had several shows, was
well received in the press,

00:45:16.550 --> 00:45:18.820
but the public did
not fulfill his hopes.

00:45:18.820 --> 00:45:21.500
At the end of 1932
he left for Paris

00:45:21.500 --> 00:45:24.960
where he'd met his old friends,
Tutor and Don Wilkinson.

00:45:24.960 --> 00:45:27.280
Of Don, [inaudible]
said I was asked

00:45:27.280 --> 00:45:28.700
to paint the most
beautiful woman

00:45:28.700 --> 00:45:31.440
in the world, but I failed.

00:45:31.440 --> 00:45:33.360
She had been so [inaudible]
when she was

00:45:33.360 --> 00:45:37.230
in [inaudible] before
world war 1

00:45:37.230 --> 00:45:39.330
and now she refused
the painting finding it

00:45:39.330 --> 00:45:43.810
to austere, or statue like.

00:45:43.810 --> 00:45:45.110
He also painted some

00:45:45.110 --> 00:45:47.440
of his nicest female
portraits during this visit.

00:45:47.440 --> 00:45:51.390
His subjects were mostly
friends and [inaudible] cousins

00:45:51.390 --> 00:45:52.690
of Antoinette [inaudible].

00:45:52.690 --> 00:45:56.510
In 1934.

00:45:56.510 --> 00:46:03.040
[ Background noise ]

00:46:03.040 --> 00:46:06.110
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS HOLBROOK:
On the way back to Austria

00:46:06.110 --> 00:46:09.170
from Paris, [inaudible] stopped
at [inaudible] near up Strasburg

00:46:09.170 --> 00:46:14.330
to visit his patrons and
friends, the [inaudible] family.

00:46:14.330 --> 00:46:16.370
They were close friends
of Thomas [inaudible]

00:46:16.370 --> 00:46:17.770
and his wife [inaudible].

00:46:17.770 --> 00:46:21.410
They became converted
to Roman Catholicism

00:46:21.410 --> 00:46:23.630
and thought it their duty
to build a small chapel

00:46:23.630 --> 00:46:27.120
on their own property,
adjacent to the Parish Church

00:46:27.120 --> 00:46:29.690
which then did and
now still does,

00:46:29.690 --> 00:46:32.430
serve both Protestants
and Catholics.

00:46:32.430 --> 00:46:35.640
[inaudible] knowing the task was
possible, offered his services

00:46:35.640 --> 00:46:37.660
and was offered the job.

00:46:37.660 --> 00:46:40.640
The remarkable thing about the
chapel is that is showcases all

00:46:40.640 --> 00:46:42.170
of Victor's skills and talents.

00:46:42.170 --> 00:46:45.630
It incorporates his
philosophy and world view.

00:46:45.630 --> 00:46:50.290
He created it as a prism with
a quarter prism on top, a door,

00:46:50.290 --> 00:46:52.830
a window, all out
of local stone used

00:46:52.830 --> 00:46:55.470
for the cathedral in Strasburg.

00:46:55.470 --> 00:46:59.900
He worked alongside the masons,
sculptured figures on each side

00:46:59.900 --> 00:47:03.470
of the door, crafted all
the interior appointments,

00:47:03.470 --> 00:47:06.070
drew plans for the stone
altar, the holy water fount,

00:47:06.070 --> 00:47:08.060
the candlesticks and chalice.

00:47:08.060 --> 00:47:10.950
He painted the ceiling
beams and finally,

00:47:10.950 --> 00:47:12.680
was able to place a crucifix

00:47:12.680 --> 00:47:17.310
over the altar upon his
return to Europe in 1957.

00:47:17.310 --> 00:47:19.650
He worked on the
chapel for 2 years.

00:47:19.650 --> 00:47:22.960
While there, he carved into
the marble library mantle

00:47:22.960 --> 00:47:25.190
at [inaudible] suggestion.

00:47:25.190 --> 00:47:28.970
Thomas [inaudible]
requirements were a work of art,

00:47:28.970 --> 00:47:33.920
beauty and truth, refined
from Aristotle, [inaudible],

00:47:33.920 --> 00:47:40.670
reflecting the wholeness, the
unity of the work, its harmony

00:47:40.670 --> 00:47:43.990
and its rhythm which
combine to reveal a radiance

00:47:43.990 --> 00:47:48.410
that arrests the eye, stills
the mind and enchants the heart.

00:47:48.410 --> 00:47:52.430
True art, genuine art, is thus
the vehicle for transformation

00:47:52.430 --> 00:47:55.500
for spiritual growth
because is made whole

00:47:55.500 --> 00:47:58.140
through an integrating
spiritual gesture.

00:47:58.140 --> 00:48:02.250
It lifts us up to
apprehend the sublime.

00:48:02.250 --> 00:48:05.810
In 1935, [inaudible]
received an award

00:48:05.810 --> 00:48:08.160
by the Austrian government,
the golden medallion

00:48:08.160 --> 00:48:12.610
from the [inaudible] house
for services to the arts.

00:48:12.610 --> 00:48:16.950
In summer of 36, [inaudible]
was asked by Anna [inaudible],

00:48:16.950 --> 00:48:19.140
Conrad's widow, to
come to [inaudible]

00:48:19.140 --> 00:48:24.030
and to direct a school organized
as a workshop with apprentices

00:48:24.030 --> 00:48:27.380
and funded by the Vienna
Academy of Fine Arts.

00:48:27.380 --> 00:48:29.900
His school offered classes
in painting, printing,

00:48:29.900 --> 00:48:34.300
book binding, calligraphy, wood
working and cabinet making.

00:48:34.300 --> 00:48:36.740
[inaudible] again
established his press

00:48:36.740 --> 00:48:39.110
and the school operated
for 2 years.

00:48:39.110 --> 00:48:44.800
In 1937, [inaudible] was
offered a post at the Academy

00:48:44.800 --> 00:48:50.030
of fine Arts in Vienna and he
accepted the offer in early 38.

00:48:50.030 --> 00:48:55.140
He established his press
then in Vienna, but by March,

00:48:55.140 --> 00:48:57.010
the German annexation
of Austria was complete.

00:48:57.010 --> 00:48:58.310
[ Background noise ]

00:48:58.310 --> 00:49:01.030
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS HOLBROOK: A
former student at the academy,

00:49:01.030 --> 00:49:04.740
now the German chancellor and
head of the Austrian government.

00:49:04.740 --> 00:49:06.040
[inaudible] had been a member

00:49:06.040 --> 00:49:08.380
of a politically conservative
organization opposed

00:49:08.380 --> 00:49:12.100
to the annexation which was
the reason the academy gave

00:49:12.100 --> 00:49:15.010
when they notified him that
he could no longer teach.

00:49:15.010 --> 00:49:17.390
He was allowed to retain
his studio temporarily.

00:49:17.390 --> 00:49:21.130
He and his family
began a waiting game,

00:49:21.130 --> 00:49:24.860
but at least nobody every
attacked Victor's art

00:49:24.860 --> 00:49:26.790
as degenerate.

00:49:26.790 --> 00:49:31.720
In august 1939, he was retired
indefinitely from the academy.

00:49:31.720 --> 00:49:33.640
[inaudible] was afraid
he would be coopted

00:49:33.640 --> 00:49:37.390
as a propaganda artist for the
3rd Reich and knew he could not

00:49:37.390 --> 00:49:40.570
at any rate work under the
Nazi yolk with any freedom.

00:49:40.570 --> 00:49:44.700
In the spring of 39, he's
already writing to Edward Bruce

00:49:44.700 --> 00:49:49.500
at the WPA, Fritz Cradle now in
self-imposed exile in New York,

00:49:49.500 --> 00:49:52.610
Nicholas [inaudible] then
teaching at Well's College

00:49:52.610 --> 00:49:56.650
and [inaudible] and the
Wilkinson's in France.

00:49:56.650 --> 00:49:58.570
Warned by American
friends and beginning

00:49:58.570 --> 00:50:01.030
to realize completely the
political consequences

00:50:01.030 --> 00:50:04.120
of remaining in Austria,
[inaudible] was willing

00:50:04.120 --> 00:50:07.630
to face economic
insecurity abroad.

00:50:07.630 --> 00:50:10.070
[inaudible] succeeded in
getting [inaudible] a position

00:50:10.070 --> 00:50:14.510
in the art department at Well's
College in September of 39.

00:50:14.510 --> 00:50:19.120
He and Rosa left for [inaudible]
as if for a weekend trip,

00:50:19.120 --> 00:50:23.030
painting on the German general's
portrait that was on his,

00:50:23.030 --> 00:50:26.360
I mean the Austrian generals
portrait that was on his easel

00:50:26.360 --> 00:50:29.750
in the studio, a
little Hitler mustache.

00:50:29.750 --> 00:50:33.080
[inaudible] had arranged a
travel by ship and they sailed

00:50:33.080 --> 00:50:36.420
for New York without
anything but a bag,

00:50:36.420 --> 00:50:39.660
arriving in September of 39.

00:50:39.660 --> 00:50:43.760
At Well's, [inaudible]
assumed his professorship

00:50:43.760 --> 00:50:46.830
and not having any of
his own type, typographer

00:50:46.830 --> 00:50:49.940
and printer Joseph [inaudible]
in New York, gave him some

00:50:49.940 --> 00:50:53.240
of his spiral type to use.

00:50:53.240 --> 00:50:54.540
While at Wells,

00:50:54.540 --> 00:50:57.620
victor established the
Well's college press.

00:50:57.620 --> 00:51:02.090
He became an American citizen
in 1945, cut the 14-point size

00:51:02.090 --> 00:51:04.410
of the American [inaudible]
type.

00:51:04.410 --> 00:51:10.590
In [inaudible], he completed
3 panels and this portrait

00:51:10.590 --> 00:51:14.180
of [inaudible] who was
a ballerina and head

00:51:14.180 --> 00:51:19.490
of the [inaudible]
foundation in New York.

00:51:19.490 --> 00:51:23.740
The Austrian peasant saint,
Saint Notburga, commissioned

00:51:23.740 --> 00:51:28.490
by Maria von Trap, also in exile
in the United States as well

00:51:28.490 --> 00:51:33.400
as a mythological panel of the
hunchback Aesop and [inaudible],

00:51:33.400 --> 00:51:41.070
and a panel of depicting
Christ and the money changers.

00:51:41.070 --> 00:51:46.840
In 1948, the renaissance society
at the University of Chicago

00:51:46.840 --> 00:51:48.630
under the direction of
[inaudible] old friend

00:51:48.630 --> 00:51:52.630
from Florence, [inaudible],
arranged a retrospective exhibit

00:51:52.630 --> 00:51:55.300
of [inaudible] work at
the Newberry library.

00:51:55.300 --> 00:51:57.750
Raymond McClain, president
of Transylvania College

00:51:57.750 --> 00:52:00.970
in Lexington and its board
share Joseph [inaudible] were

00:52:00.970 --> 00:52:03.000
especially invited.

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:06.090
[inaudible] was nearing
mandatory retirement at Wells

00:52:06.090 --> 00:52:09.110
and [inaudible] of the
[inaudible] foundry

00:52:09.110 --> 00:52:12.860
who had known victor and was
a friend of [inaudible] along

00:52:12.860 --> 00:52:16.890
with other Chicago friends hoped
Transylvania might call victor's

00:52:16.890 --> 00:52:19.060
artist in residence.

00:52:19.060 --> 00:52:22.860
McClain and Graves were amazed
at the depth and breadth

00:52:22.860 --> 00:52:26.430
of victor's talent and craft
and immediately did invite him

00:52:26.430 --> 00:52:29.360
to come to Lexington
without consulting any

00:52:29.360 --> 00:52:32.010
of the Transylvania
board members.

00:52:32.010 --> 00:52:33.590
[inaudible] accepted and
with only a hand shake,

00:52:33.590 --> 00:52:34.960
it was settled.

00:52:34.960 --> 00:52:37.770
As McClain later said
in an oral history,

00:52:37.770 --> 00:52:40.890
we did things differently
in those days.

00:52:40.890 --> 00:52:43.990
And so, in the fall of 1948,
[inaudible] began his position

00:52:43.990 --> 00:52:47.090
as artist in residence
at Transylvania College

00:52:47.090 --> 00:52:48.550
in Lexington, Kentucky.

00:52:48.550 --> 00:52:51.040
Established his press, now

00:52:51.040 --> 00:52:53.560
with his own American
[inaudible] type,

00:52:53.560 --> 00:52:57.690
the [inaudible] again operated

00:52:57.690 --> 00:53:01.410
and began its run
in the bluegrass.

00:53:01.410 --> 00:53:03.780
[inaudible] time in
Lexington was peaceful.

00:53:03.780 --> 00:53:07.310
Of course, he acquired a new
circle of friends and patrons.

00:53:07.310 --> 00:53:10.270
Teaching, and as a result
without any financial worry,

00:53:10.270 --> 00:53:15.030
he could work on projects
that we wanted to do.

00:53:15.030 --> 00:53:18.210
Rosa [inaudible] died in 1954.

00:53:19.410 --> 00:53:23.260
The following year, [inaudible]
married their mutual,

00:53:23.260 --> 00:53:24.560
well their friend,
Caroline [inaudible]

00:53:24.560 --> 00:53:26.690
who had been Victor's apprentice

00:53:26.690 --> 00:53:30.100
and helped Rosa during
her final illness.

00:53:30.100 --> 00:53:32.580
He cut the 18-point American
[inaudible] in Lexington

00:53:32.580 --> 00:53:37.740
and the 14 point
[inaudible] type.

00:53:37.740 --> 00:53:43.660
He completed 5 portraits
including one of Raymond McClain

00:53:43.660 --> 00:53:47.300
and our Kentucky
[inaudible], John Jacob Niles.

00:53:47.300 --> 00:53:52.090
He painted 8 panels on
[inaudible], crucifixes,

00:53:52.090 --> 00:53:54.210
3 different versions
of varying size.

00:53:54.210 --> 00:53:55.510
One for the chapel
in [inaudible],

00:53:55.510 --> 00:54:00.420
one for Thomas Merton who wanted
it in his [inaudible] chapel

00:54:00.420 --> 00:54:05.190
at [inaudible] and another
one that he retained himself.

00:54:05.190 --> 00:54:08.510
He did the 4th and 5th versions
of Christ and the adulteress

00:54:08.510 --> 00:54:14.670
and these 2 tryptic on the
left crowning the young Christ

00:54:14.670 --> 00:54:20.050
and memory and her 9 daughters,
the muses, and he worked on,

00:54:20.050 --> 00:54:25.460
but did not finish his lass
tryptic, the resurrection.

00:54:25.460 --> 00:54:29.510
Do I have time to say
something on [inaudible]?

00:54:29.510 --> 00:54:32.280
[ Background noise ]

00:54:32.280 --> 00:54:35.670
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS HOLBROOK:
Are we doing all right?

00:54:35.670 --> 00:54:39.270
Well, the [inaudible] Sophia
was commissioned as a Madonna

00:54:39.270 --> 00:54:42.710
and child and as Victor
was working on it,

00:54:42.710 --> 00:54:46.840
the child became a young man
and the woman, the Madonna,

00:54:46.840 --> 00:54:50.320
became almost Amazonian
in proportion.

00:54:50.320 --> 00:54:53.740
And Thomas Merton came to
the dentist in Lexington,

00:54:53.740 --> 00:54:56.700
which was a way that
he could escape

00:54:56.700 --> 00:55:00.640
and see his friends
[inaudible] and at lunch,

00:55:00.640 --> 00:55:04.740
Merton was observing the panel
on the easel and he said,

00:55:04.740 --> 00:55:12.100
who are these people and
victor said I no longer know.

00:55:12.100 --> 00:55:16.160
Merton thought of the line from
proverbs, Wisdom will honor you

00:55:16.160 --> 00:55:19.800
if you love her, she will place
on your head a fair garland,

00:55:19.800 --> 00:55:22.280
she will crown you
with a crown of glory.

00:55:22.280 --> 00:55:27.030
And so, Merton said this
is [inaudible] Sophia

00:55:27.030 --> 00:55:29.050
and crowing the young Christ.

00:55:29.050 --> 00:55:32.310
Merton then wrote his little
meditation on the holy hours

00:55:32.310 --> 00:55:35.450
of the day called
[inaudible] Sophia.

00:55:35.450 --> 00:55:40.480
In the muses, which is in, at
the University of San Francisco,

00:55:40.480 --> 00:55:43.890
Victor did something
that he often did do,

00:55:43.890 --> 00:55:50.490
make use of his former sitter's
faces in another context

00:55:50.490 --> 00:55:57.870
and Mrs. Tudor Wilkinson
[inaudible] as the head

00:55:57.870 --> 00:56:03.270
of Urania and when Victor
told her she was going to be

00:56:03.270 --> 00:56:06.420
in his tryptic she wrote a post
card and said oh dear Victor,

00:56:06.420 --> 00:56:10.180
I'm so happy I'm in your tryptic
when my body is moldering

00:56:10.180 --> 00:56:14.710
in the ground, my, I will
still be measuring the skies.

00:56:14.710 --> 00:56:18.470
[inaudible] was awarded
an honorary doctor

00:56:18.470 --> 00:56:20.770
of humanities degree by the
University of [inaudible]

00:56:20.770 --> 00:56:25.220
in 1960 in the North Carolina
Museum of Art at Raleigh mounted

00:56:25.220 --> 00:56:29.200
in retrospective
exhibition in 1965.

00:56:29.200 --> 00:56:33.300
[inaudible] died in Lexington
on the 10th of July 1967.

00:56:33.300 --> 00:56:36.840
Raymond McClain, former
president of Transylvania,

00:56:36.840 --> 00:56:39.030
read the burial service
concluding

00:56:39.030 --> 00:56:41.100
with this final evaluation.

00:56:41.100 --> 00:56:44.660
It was his genius to unify
these gifts in his life.

00:56:44.660 --> 00:56:51.460
He made no distinctions so far
as I can tell between the arts

00:56:51.460 --> 00:56:54.380
and the crafts, even more
between the fine arts

00:56:54.380 --> 00:56:56.860
and the supposed
lesser categories.

00:56:56.860 --> 00:57:00.370
There was just as much artistry,
just a much craftsmanship,

00:57:00.370 --> 00:57:03.400
just as much attention to
composition, just as marriage

00:57:03.400 --> 00:57:07.090
with form and function, just
as much discipline, technique

00:57:07.090 --> 00:57:09.710
and production, whether
the work were carpentry

00:57:09.710 --> 00:57:12.020
or punch cutting or painting.

00:57:12.020 --> 00:57:15.020
This gave Victor the power
of undivided wholeness

00:57:15.020 --> 00:57:18.380
and reduced potential
complexity to simplicity.

00:57:18.380 --> 00:57:21.060
These are attributes
of genius and results

00:57:21.060 --> 00:57:25.700
of enormous self-discipline
exercised over the years.

00:57:25.700 --> 00:57:28.510
He's lifted his work to
the level of the universal,

00:57:28.510 --> 00:57:32.340
lifted it above the moment
and gave it to the ages.

00:57:32.340 --> 00:57:35.650
Let us make no mistake about
Victor, he was a simple man,

00:57:35.650 --> 00:57:38.770
but it was an achieved
simplicity.

00:57:38.770 --> 00:57:40.850
He was a highly sophisticated
person,

00:57:40.850 --> 00:57:42.900
well read in several languages,

00:57:42.900 --> 00:57:44.710
conversed with the
best minds ever

00:57:44.710 --> 00:57:46.600
to have reduced their
thoughts to poetry

00:57:46.600 --> 00:57:48.970
or prose on the printed page.

00:57:48.970 --> 00:57:51.780
His simplicity was the
result of education,

00:57:51.780 --> 00:57:53.520
of continuing thought.

00:57:53.520 --> 00:57:55.610
His technique embodied
a constant search

00:57:55.610 --> 00:57:57.790
for better ways of doing things.

00:57:57.790 --> 00:58:01.260
His power was rooted in a
highly sensitized intuition,

00:58:01.260 --> 00:58:03.650
refined by unremitting
work and dedicated

00:58:03.650 --> 00:58:07.810
to a purpose beyond his
immediate personal status.

00:58:07.810 --> 00:58:09.650
It is no accident that
he worked [inaudible],

00:58:09.650 --> 00:58:15.910
the moto which was carved in
the portico of the Jesuit church

00:58:15.910 --> 00:58:19.670
in Vienna which had
overshadowed his childhood gains

00:58:19.670 --> 00:58:22.510
and nurtured his
life as an artist.

00:58:22.510 --> 00:58:25.410
He paid the price to
deserve this distinction.

00:58:25.410 --> 00:58:28.650
He could be so withdrawn
from the world because he was

00:58:28.650 --> 00:58:31.400
so thoroughly its product.

00:58:31.400 --> 00:58:38.100
And this is a late
portrait of our [inaudible],

00:58:38.100 --> 00:58:44.580
collector of folk songs and
musician John Jacob Niles

00:58:44.580 --> 00:58:50.100
and completely, accidentally,

00:58:50.100 --> 00:58:55.600
Johnny's 126th birthday is
Saturday and the friends

00:58:55.600 --> 00:58:59.490
in Lexington have contributed
to an historical marker

00:58:59.490 --> 00:59:04.730
to be placed on the
[inaudible] road at Boot Hill,

00:59:04.730 --> 00:59:07.750
the Nile's farm in Clark County.

00:59:09.850 --> 00:59:13.600
And Victor, and this
is a perfect example

00:59:13.600 --> 00:59:14.960
of Victor's portraits here.

00:59:14.960 --> 00:59:20.730
Everyone looks far more austere
than they were in reality

00:59:20.730 --> 00:59:24.200
and there's another similar
portrait of the mayor

00:59:24.200 --> 00:59:30.170
of Louisville, Charlie Farnsley
who was just a terrible comedian

00:59:30.170 --> 00:59:34.590
and yet he looks very
dignified in the picture.

00:59:38.100 --> 00:59:40.590
So, that's all I have to
say, but I'll be happy

00:59:40.590 --> 00:59:43.510
to answer any questions
if I can.

