01:00:18.700 --> 01:00:20.330
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS HOLBROOK:
Thank you for coming.

01:00:20.330 --> 01:00:23.060
&gt;&gt; What was it that
offended the Nazis,

01:00:23.060 --> 01:00:24.360
that required the [inaudible].

01:00:24.360 --> 01:00:25.660
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS
HOLBROOK: Well,

01:00:25.660 --> 01:00:27.110
[inaudible] didn't
have to leave.

01:00:27.110 --> 01:00:32.810
He just felt because he knew
he would not have any artistic

01:00:32.810 --> 01:00:40.240
freedom and he had no intention
of becoming a propaganda artist

01:00:40.240 --> 01:00:43.310
which his paintings,
as it were idealized,

01:00:43.310 --> 01:00:49.110
figures would have been
perfect for the Nazi program.

01:00:49.110 --> 01:00:50.410
&gt;&gt; Did he [inaudible]?

01:00:50.410 --> 01:00:54.660
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS HOLBROOK: Yes,
but he was forbidden to teach.

01:00:54.660 --> 01:01:02.070
The excuse was that he belonged
to this conservative party

01:01:02.070 --> 01:01:04.430
that was against the annexation.

01:01:04.430 --> 01:01:08.370
So, there was really no reason
that they needed to fire him,

01:01:08.370 --> 01:01:10.860
but I'm sure, but
it happily worked

01:01:10.860 --> 01:01:13.500
out to everyone's advantage
except the [inaudible]

01:01:13.500 --> 01:01:14.910
which was replaced by the.

01:01:14.910 --> 01:01:19.340
I showed the original memorial
was a bust from the waist up

01:01:19.340 --> 01:01:23.450
and the marble plaque underneath
it and Victor had had a head,

01:01:23.450 --> 01:01:26.550
just the head cast for
him to keep at the time

01:01:26.550 --> 01:01:33.010
of the original casting and
they were able to make a mold

01:01:33.010 --> 01:01:42.790
from the cast head and recast
another head that I'm told is

01:01:42.790 --> 01:01:44.340
in the [inaudible]
house again in Salzburg,

01:01:44.340 --> 01:01:45.640
but I haven't yet seen it.

01:01:45.640 --> 01:01:51.730
I hope to get to
Salzburg before too long.

01:01:51.730 --> 01:01:53.660
&gt;&gt; Another question.

01:01:53.660 --> 01:01:56.960
Was the relationship of the
[inaudible] long standing?

01:01:56.960 --> 01:01:58.260
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS HOLBROOK: Yes.

01:01:58.260 --> 01:02:00.690
Well, it was very important.

01:02:00.690 --> 01:02:05.690
It allowed him, the press,
to really be started.

01:02:05.690 --> 01:02:13.540
Edgar Sr. gave Victor I think
$400 a month for 2 years

01:02:13.540 --> 01:02:16.750
and Edgar Jr. After, then
the depression hit of course

01:02:16.750 --> 01:02:20.470
and Edgar Jr. said I'm getting
an allowance from father,

01:02:20.470 --> 01:02:22.560
I will have it and
give you half of it.

01:02:22.560 --> 01:02:26.780
He was still there in
the studio, which he did,

01:02:26.780 --> 01:02:29.800
and Edgar Jr. although,
you know,

01:02:29.800 --> 01:02:32.480
he had this fabulous
art collection,

01:02:32.480 --> 01:02:37.600
but it was mostly contemporary
works, but he had these several.

01:02:37.600 --> 01:02:46.340
I mean, he was devoted to Victor
and wrote a very nice meditation

01:02:46.340 --> 01:02:49.120
for the 3rd volume the
[inaudible] press publication

01:02:49.120 --> 01:02:51.530
Victor [inaudible], an artist's
testament about his time

01:02:51.530 --> 01:02:53.980
and his experience
in the studio.

01:02:53.980 --> 01:02:56.510
And he, when Victor died,
he sent the large portrait

01:02:56.510 --> 01:03:01.050
of Victor to Caroline
of, which he had in his,

01:03:01.050 --> 01:03:04.190
stored away somewhere
probably with the paint brush

01:03:04.190 --> 01:03:06.230
and the [inaudible] on which
Caroline then donated along

01:03:06.230 --> 01:03:08.920
with the silver point
and the, that one copy

01:03:08.920 --> 01:03:13.090
of the [inaudible] self-portrait

01:03:15.850 --> 01:03:18.040
to the national portrait
gallery.

01:03:18.040 --> 01:03:22.140
So, it's here somewhere and
would be nice to see it again.

01:03:22.140 --> 01:03:25.050
But, so yes, the
[inaudible] were and Caroline

01:03:25.050 --> 01:03:28.120
and Edgar Jr. corresponded
till he died.

01:03:28.120 --> 01:03:29.420
&gt;&gt; Those are preserved?

01:03:29.420 --> 01:03:30.720
[inaudible].

01:03:30.720 --> 01:03:32.020
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS HOLBROOK:
Oh yes, the art isn't.

01:03:32.020 --> 01:03:33.320
The correspondence
should be here,

01:03:33.320 --> 01:03:34.620
all the [inaudible]
correspondence.

01:03:34.620 --> 01:03:35.920
The Wilkinson correspondence,

01:03:35.920 --> 01:03:40.840
the [inaudible] correspondence,
there's over, Victor.

01:03:40.840 --> 01:03:44.930
I mean, there's over
400, I think,

01:03:44.930 --> 01:03:48.710
envelopes of correspondence
in the collection here.

01:03:48.710 --> 01:03:53.970
&gt;&gt; ERIC FRAZIER: So, part of
Paul's coming to give this talk

01:03:53.970 --> 01:03:58.310
and talk [inaudible]
tomorrow is, is also a bit

01:03:58.310 --> 01:04:09.310
of a celebration in
rehousing and publishing

01:04:09.310 --> 01:04:18.670
and posting the revised binding
[inaudible] for the collection.

01:04:18.670 --> 01:04:25.460
And so, the collection
is broke up into,

01:04:25.460 --> 01:04:29.680
it's a wonderful collection.

01:04:33.140 --> 01:04:35.730
We have correspondence exhibits,

01:04:35.730 --> 01:04:39.770
exhibit publications,
photographs.

01:04:39.770 --> 01:04:42.020
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS HOLBROOK:
Reviews and critiques.

01:04:42.020 --> 01:04:48.080
&gt;&gt; ERIC FRAZIER: As well
as some artifacts and some

01:04:48.080 --> 01:04:52.710
of his printing blocks.

01:04:52.710 --> 01:04:55.150
And yeah, so that's [inaudible]
collection exists here

01:04:55.150 --> 01:04:56.450
at the [inaudible] and
special collections.

01:04:56.450 --> 01:04:57.750
It was posted earlier this week

01:04:57.750 --> 01:04:59.050
