01:05:23.740 --> 01:05:25.040
&gt;&gt; ERIC FRAZIER:
Assembly line up of.

01:05:25.040 --> 01:05:26.740
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS
HOLBROOK: Several helpers.

01:05:26.740 --> 01:05:28.040
Yes Mam.

01:05:28.040 --> 01:05:30.760
&gt;&gt; Where are the presses now?

01:05:30.760 --> 01:05:32.060
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS
HOLBROOK: Well,

01:05:32.060 --> 01:05:33.550
mysteriously the 2
wooden presses were left

01:05:33.550 --> 01:05:37.350
in Victor's studio in
Vienna when he left in 39.

01:05:37.350 --> 01:05:40.520
Mysteriously, one of
them found its way the

01:05:40.520 --> 01:05:44.990
to the Gutenberg's last
house in [inaudible].

01:05:44.990 --> 01:05:48.520
So, it's a part of
the collection there.

01:05:48.520 --> 01:05:51.430
The other wooden press is
at the King Library Press.

01:05:51.430 --> 01:05:56.430
It along with a lot of
things from the studio came

01:05:56.430 --> 01:06:01.000
to Lexington in 1955
and friends of Victor's

01:06:01.000 --> 01:06:04.990
in Lexington bought the wooden
press from him and donated it

01:06:04.990 --> 01:06:08.790
to the King Library for use
in the press there in order

01:06:08.790 --> 01:06:13.580
to help support Victor's
life in Lexington.

01:06:13.580 --> 01:06:19.570
And the, Victor had an
iron press at Wells College

01:06:19.570 --> 01:06:25.760
which was left there and the,
we, they reopened the press

01:06:25.760 --> 01:06:30.520
in 1993 I think and it
is, they have a curator

01:06:30.520 --> 01:06:33.940
who comes I think every
other year, a hummer fellow,

01:06:33.940 --> 01:06:37.280
a printer who comes
and does work there.

01:06:37.280 --> 01:06:44.610
And Victor got an iron press
in, after he came to Lexington

01:06:44.610 --> 01:06:50.600
which he, which is still in
Lexington with Caroline's nephew

01:06:50.600 --> 01:06:55.130
who also learned to print.

01:06:55.130 --> 01:06:59.060
&gt;&gt; The wooden presses
were [inaudible].

01:07:00.540 --> 01:07:01.920
&gt;&gt; DR. PAUL EVANS HOLBROOK:
There is a press still

01:07:01.920 --> 01:07:06.540
in the [inaudible] Library
in Florence that was thought,

01:07:06.540 --> 01:07:11.300
when Victor drew the, copied
the, drew the plans for it,

01:07:11.300 --> 01:07:17.360
though to be the 15th century
Remundy Press and [inaudible],

01:07:17.360 --> 01:07:21.730
who it was and I've showed
she's no longer there,

01:07:21.730 --> 01:07:26.820
I mean long dead, at the
library, proved more or less

01:07:26.820 --> 01:07:30.700
to everyone's satisfaction
that it was an Napoleonic copy

01:07:30.700 --> 01:07:32.590
of the original Remundy press.

01:07:32.590 --> 01:07:37.610
But, still, an old
press and its,

01:07:37.610 --> 01:07:41.390
Victor and [inaudible] did
a very nice job with it.

01:07:41.390 --> 01:07:44.240
It's a beautiful
press and we use it.

01:07:44.240 --> 01:07:50.530
I just had a student this
semester who wanted to do a poet

01:07:50.530 --> 01:07:56.900
in MFA candidate in poetry
did a, wanted to do a poem

01:07:56.900 --> 01:08:01.060
and used the wooden
press to do the poem.

01:08:01.060 --> 01:08:04.370
He wanted to, we happened
to have a Buick woodcut,

01:08:04.370 --> 01:08:08.780
a small heron, tiny
one that Bob Middleton

01:08:08.780 --> 01:08:12.680
who had accumulated a large
collection of Buick cuts

01:08:12.680 --> 01:08:16.400
and at his cherry
burn press in Chicago,

01:08:16.400 --> 01:08:21.710
printed 2 different
volumes of Buick images.

01:08:21.710 --> 01:08:26.700
So, we use the image of the
heron in this, with this poem.

01:08:26.700 --> 01:08:29.960
And I thought the wooden press
would be the gentlest way

01:08:29.960 --> 01:08:38.670
to print this lock that was done
in 1730 or whenever it was done.

01:08:38.670 --> 01:08:43.700
So, we're, we are still
very much using the press

01:08:43.700 --> 01:08:46.490
and I have Caroline, when
she, we quit printing,

01:08:46.490 --> 01:08:49.450
the last book we printed
at the anvil press

01:08:49.450 --> 01:08:54.680
which was her final imprint,
Thomas Merton's 4 poems

01:08:54.680 --> 01:09:01.070
in French and Merton having
been born in Prague, France.

01:09:01.070 --> 01:09:06.750
And she gave me the press and
the contents of the press room

01:09:06.750 --> 01:09:11.120
and I transferred them to the
King Library where I assume

01:09:11.120 --> 01:09:13.000
as long as it lasts, will be.

01:09:13.000 --> 01:09:15.440
I mean, I will eventually
completely donate it

01:09:15.440 --> 01:09:17.690
to the King Library
unless they close the press

01:09:17.690 --> 01:09:19.490
and I have to take it home.

01:09:19.490 --> 01:09:23.920
But, I imagine in my old age
going to the press and using it

01:09:23.920 --> 01:09:27.790
as long as I please even
if I'm no longer there.

01:09:27.790 --> 01:09:29.590
So.

